[{"note_id" : "14840724-DS-21", "charttime" : "2116-03-25T00:00:00", "storetime" : "2116-03-25T17:13:00", "note_seq" : 21, "text_snippet" : " 
Name:  ___                Unit No:   ___
 
Admission Date:  ___              Discharge Date:   ___
 
Date of Birth:  ___             Sex:   F
 
Service: SURGERY
 
Allergies: 
Etodolac / Erythromycin Base
 
Attending: ___
 
Chief Complaint:
Right breast cancer.

 
Major Surgical or Invasive Procedure:
Completion right axillary dissection.

 
History of Present Illness:
The patient is a ___ female who presented to Dr. ___ 
in ___ with a diagnosis of right breast cancer. She 
was taken to the operating room on ___ and underwent 
a right mastectomy with tissue expander placement and right 
sentinel lymph node biopsy.Operative pathology returned on 
___ sentinel lymph nodes positive 
for
metastatic disease. In-breast disease with keeping with the 
clinical picture.  It was an invasive carcinoma measuring 2.6 
cm, grade 3.All the margins were clear.  Dr. ___ 
recommendation to proceed to completion dissection, given the 
finding of ___ sentinel lymph nodes, and additionally the 
presence of extranodal extension. She did undergo staging 
studies prior to returning to the operating room.  These were 
performed on ___, and did not show any evidence of 
distant metastatic disease.

 
Past Medical History:
Right breast cancer
PSH:
Right mastectomy with tissue expander placement and right 
sentinel lymph node biopsy.  
 
Social History:
___
Family History:
Non contributory
 
Physical Exam:
VS:98.7 56 90/60 18 99%RA
General: AAOx3, NAD
HEENT: NC/AT, mucosa moist and pink, sclerae anicteric
Cardiac: RRR
Pulmonary: CTAB
Abdomen: Soft, NT/ND
Wound site: R axillary dressing c/d/i, JP drain intact 
serosanguinous fluid.
Extremities:warm well perfused, no ___ edema 
 
Brief Hospital Course:
___ year old female with history of right breast cancer who 
recently underwent right mastectomy with tissue expander 
placement,right sentinel lymph node biopsy. She now presents for 
completion right axillary dissection and was taken to the 
operating room on ___. The patient tolerated the procedure 
well and was transferred to the PACU and admitted to the floor 
for further monitoring.

Neuro:Postoperatively her pain was managed with Dilaudid PCA 
which was titrated up accordingly and she was slowly restarted 
on her home pain medication regimen. She received Valium/Ativan 
as needed with good effect. POD 1, her PCA was weaned and she 
had good pain control.
Cardiac:She had no cardiac issues and vital signs were closely 
monitored and remained stable.
Pulmonary:She had no respiratory concerns.
GI/GU: Her diet was  appropriately advanced which was tolerated 
well and she voided spontaneously without any issues.
Incision:Her right axillary dressing remained intact without any 
signs of infection or hematoma.Her JP drain was intact with 
acceptable amounts of serosanguineous fluid.
DVT Prophylaxis:The patient wore pneumatic compression boots, 
and was encouraged to get up and ambulate as early as possible. 
POD 1,she had adequate pain control and was deemed appropriate 
for discharge with ___ for drain care.
 
Medications on Admission:
___: duloxetine 60', gabapentin 800''', levothyroxine 50', 
lorazepam ___ TID:PRN, Oxycodone Q6H:PRN, tramadol 100 TID:PRN 
 

 
Discharge Medications:
1. Acetaminophen 650 mg PO Q4H:PRN pain 
2. Gabapentin 800 mg PO TID 
3. Duloxetine 60 mg PO DAILY 
4. Levothyroxine Sodium 50 mcg PO DAILY 
5. TraMADOL (Ultram) 50 mg PO BID 
6. OxycoDONE (Immediate Release)  ___ mg PO Q3H:PRN pain 
RX *oxycodone 5 mg ___ tablet(s) by mouth every three (3) hours 
Disp #*80 Tablet Refills:*0
7. Lorazepam 0.5-1 mg PO TID:PRN pain 
8. Diazepam 5 mg PO Q8H:PRN pain Duration: 3 Days 
RX *diazepam 5 mg 1 tablet(s) by mouth every eight (8) hours 
Disp #*15 Tablet Refills:*0

 
Discharge Disposition:
Home With Service
 
Facility:
___
 
Discharge Diagnosis:
Right breast cancer.

 
Discharge Condition:
Mental Status: Clear and coherent.
Level of Consciousness: Alert and interactive.
Activity Status: Ambulatory - Independent.

 
Discharge Instructions:
Personal Care:  
1. You may keep your incision covered with a clean, sterile 
gauze that you change daily. 
2. Clean around the drain site(s), where the tubing exits the 
skin, with soap and water.  
3. Strip drain tubing, empty bulb(s), and record output(s) ___ 
times per day.  
4. A written record of the daily output from each drain should 
be brought to every follow-up appointment. your drains will be 
removed as soon as possible when the daily output tapers off to 
an acceptable amount.  
5. You may shower daily with assistance as needed. Be sure to 
secure your upper drains to a laniard that hangs down from your 
neck so they don't hang down and pull out. 
6. The Dermabond skin glue will begin to flake off in about ___ 
days.  
Activity:  
1. You may resume your regular diet.  
2. Walk several times a day.  
3. DO NOT lift anything heavier than 5 pounds or engage in 
strenuous activity for 6 weeks following surgery. 
Medications:  
1. Resume your regular medications unless instructed otherwise 
and take any new meds as ordered .  
2. You may take your prescribed pain medication for moderate to 
severe pain. You may switch to Tylenol or Extra Strength Tylenol 
for mild pain as directed on the packaging. Please note that 
Percocet and Vicodin have Tylenol as an active ingredient so do 
not take these meds with additional Tylenol.  
3. Take prescription pain medications for pain not relieved by 
tylenol.  
4. Take Colace, 100 mg by mouth 2 times per day, while taking 
the prescription pain medication. You may use a different 
over-the-counter stool softener if you wish.  
5. Do not drive or operate heavy machinery while taking any 
narcotic pain medication. You may have constipation when taking 
narcotic pain medications (oxycodone, percocet, vicodin, 
hydrocodone, dilaudid, etc.); you should continue drinking 
fluids, you may take stool softeners, and should eat foods that 
are high in fiber.  

Call the office IMMEDIATELY if you have any of the following:  
1. Signs of infection: fever with chills, increased redness, 
swelling, warmth or tenderness at the surgical site, or unusual 
drainage from the incision(s).  
2. A large amount of bleeding from the incision(s) or drain(s).  

3. Fever greater than 101.5 oF  
4. Severe pain NOT relieved by your medication.  
  
Return to the ER if:  
* If you are vomiting and cannot keep in fluids or your 
medications.  
* If you have shaking chills, fever greater than 101.5 (F) 
degrees or 38 (C) degrees, increased redness,swelling or 
discharge from incision, chest pain, shortness of breath, or 
anything else that is troubling you.  
* Any serious change in your symptoms, or any new symptoms that 
concern you.  
DRAIN DISCHARGE INSTRUCTIONS  
You are being discharged with drains in place. Drain care is a 
clean procedure. Wash your hands thoroughly with soap and warm 
water before performing drain care. Perform drainage care twice 
a day. Try to empty the drain at the same time each day. Pull 
the stopper out of the drainage bottle and empty the drainage 
fluid into the measuring cup. Record the amount of drainage 
fluid on the record sheet. Reestablish drain suction.  
Please assist patient with drain care. A daily log of individual 
drain outputs should be maintained and brought with patient to 
follow up appointment with Dr. ___.
 
Followup Instructions:
___

invasive ductal carcinoma and ductal carcinoma in situ. The 
patient now presents today for a left breast lumpectomy and

will be performed after needle localization since the lesion is 
not palpable.

diverticular disease with recent episode of diverticulitis 3

widow with 6 children daughter with arrythmia  
Mother, daughter and son with bipolar disorder

This is a ___ year old female who is status post left breast

difficult to wean and she was placed on 2L nasal cannula 
overnight and monitored on telemetry for continuous O2 sats. POD

MULTIVITAMIN - multivitamin capsule. 1 Capsule(s) by mouth once 
a day

 
Discharge Medications:
1. Acetaminophen 650 mg PO TID 
2. Albuterol Inhaler 2 PUFF IH PRN wheezing 
3. Amlodipine 5 mg PO DAILY 
4. Aspirin 81 mg PO DAILY 
5. Fluoxetine 20 mg PO DAILY 
6. Latanoprost 0.005% Ophth. Soln. 1 DROP BOTH EYES HS 
7. Lithium Carbonate SR (Lithobid) 600 mg PO BID 
8. OLANZapine 2.5 mg PO HS 
9. TraMADOL (Ultram) 25 mg PO Q6H:PRN pain 
10. traZODONE 25 mg PO HS:PRN insomnia 

 
Discharge Disposition:
Home
 
Discharge Diagnosis:
Left breast cancer

 
Discharge Condition:
Mental Status: Clear and coherent.
Level of Consciousness: Alert and interactive.
Activity Status: Ambulatory - Independent.

 
Discharge Instructions:
1. You may remove your surgical dressing 48 hours after your 
surgery and leave the incision open to air. 
2. You may shower daily. No baths until instructed to do so by 
___
3. You may wear a soft, non-restrictive camisole but no tight or 
underwire bras. 

Activity: 
1. You may resume your regular diet. 
2. DO NOT lift anything heavier than 5 pounds or engage in 
strenuous activity until instructed by ___. 
Medications
1. Resume your regular medications unless instructed otherwise 
and take any new meds as ordered. 
2. You may take your prescribed pain medication for moderate to 
severe pain. You may switch to Tylenol or Extra Strength Tylenol 
for mild pain as directed on the packaging. 
4. Take prescription pain medications for pain not relieved by 
tylenol. 
5.Take Colace, 100 mg by mouth 2 times per day, while taking the 
prescription pain medication. You may use a different 
over-the-counter stool softener if you wish. 
6. Do not drive or operate heavy machinery while taking any 
narcotic pain medication. You may have constipation when taking 
narcotic pain medications (oxycodone, percocet, vicodin, 
hydrocodone, dilaudid, etc.); you should continue drinking 
fluids, you may take stool softeners, and should eat foods that 
are high in fiber. 

Call the office IMMEDIATELY if you have any of the following: 
1. Signs of infection: fever with chills, increased redness, 
swelling, warmth or tenderness at the surgical site, or unusual 
drainage from the incision(s). 
2. A large amount of bleeding from the incision(s) or drain(s). 
3. Fever greater than 101.5 oF 
4. Severe pain NOT relieved by your medication. 

Return to the ER if: 
* If you are vomiting and cannot keep in fluids or your 
medications. 
* If you have shaking chills, fever greater than 101.5 (F) 
degrees or 38 (C) degrees, increased redness, swelling or 
discharge from incision, chest pain, shortness of breath, or 
anything else that is troubling you. 
* Any serious change in your symptoms, or any new symptoms that 
concern you. 

 
Followup Instructions:
___

[{"note_id" : "11489167-DS-6", "charttime" : "2183-08-25T00:00:00", "storetime" : "2183-08-25T11:39:00", "note_seq" : 6, "text_snippet" : " 
Name:  ___                   ___ No:   ___
 
Admission Date:  ___              Discharge Date:   ___
 
Date of Birth:  ___             Sex:   F
 
Service: SURGERY
 
Allergies: 
penicillin G
 
Attending: ___
 
Chief Complaint:
Bilateral Invasive Ductal Carcinoma
 
Major Surgical or Invasive Procedure:
bilateral modified radical mastectomy

 
History of Present Illness:
___ ___ female who recently self-palpated 
a mass in the left breast upper outer quadrant, underwent 
diagnostic imaging, which confirmed this finding as well as 
abnormal nodes in the left axilla.She underwent image-guided 
core needle biopsy of the left breast mass and found it to be 
invasive ductal carcinoma, grade 2, triple receptor negative. 
Fine-needle aspiration of an abnormal left axillary lymph node 
was positive for metastatic disease.Thus, she has been diagnosed 
with left breast invasive ductal carcinoma, grade 3, triple 
receptor negative with metastases to the left axillary lymph 
nodes.

 
Past Medical History:
1.  The patient has a history of a myocardial infarction at the
age of ___ in ___ in ___.  She had a cardiac catheterization
performed with a stent in the LAD placed in ___.  She then had
to have a second catheterization to evaluate the patency of the
stent.
2.  Hyperlipidemia.
3.  Hypertension.
4.  Occasional palpitations.  Her last stress test was in ___
with an ejection fraction of 42%.
5.  Diabetes mellitus, which is diet controlled.  
 
Social History:
___
Family History:
No breast or ovarian cancer.  
 
Physical Exam:
Exam on discharge:

Gen: Well appearing, NAD
CV: RRR, +S1, S2
Resp: CTAB
Wound: Incisions c/d/i with no erythema or evidence of hematoma. 
 JP drains draining serosangunous fluid.  
 
Brief Hospital Course:
Ms. ___ is a ___ ___ female with 
history of bilateral triple neg invasive ductal carcinoma, L 
grade 3, with ALN mets stage T4 N1-2 M0, R grade 3 with ALN mets 
stage T1 N1-2 M0 now s/p b/l MRM on ___. She tolerated the 
procedure well and was transferred to the PACU and admitted to 
the surgical ward for observation. Her postoperative course was 
stable. 
Post-operatively, she remained afebrile with stable vital signs; 
pain was well controlled with oral analgesia.  She remained 
stable from both a cardiovascular and pulmonary standpoint. She 
was initially NPO after the procedure, which was advanced 
sequentially to a regular diet and well tolerated; her intake 
and output were closely monitored.  Urine output remained 
adequate throughout the hospitalization. Her surgical incision 
remained dry and intact without ant signs of infection or 
hematoma. Her JP drains had acceptaple amounts of serous 
sanguineous output. She received venodyne boots throughout 
admission and early and frequent ambulation were strongly 
encouraged. She was unable to obtain ___ services due to lack of 
insurance coverage.  The patient and her husband were taught how 
to manage her JP drains as well as warning signs which should 
trigger them to reach out to the clinic or present to the ED. 
The patient and her family expressed and understanding and 
ability to manage the drains and she was subsequently discharged 
home. 
 
Medications on Admission:
The Preadmission Medication list may be inaccurate and requires 
futher investigation.
1. Ondansetron 8 mg PO Q8H:PRN nausea 
2. Prochlorperazine 10 mg PO Q6H:PRN nausea 
3. Metoprolol Tartrate 25 mg PO DAILY 
4. Atorvastatin 80 mg PO QPM 
5. Multivitamins 1 TAB PO DAILY 
6. Nitroglycerin SL 0.3 mg SL Q5MIN:PRN chest pain 
7. Aspirin 81 mg PO DAILY 

 
Discharge Medications:
1. Atorvastatin 80 mg PO QPM 
2. Metoprolol Tartrate 25 mg PO DAILY 
3. Multivitamins 1 TAB PO DAILY 
4. Ondansetron 8 mg PO Q8H:PRN nausea 
5. Prochlorperazine 10 mg PO Q6H:PRN nausea 
6. Aspirin 81 mg PO DAILY 
7. Nitroglycerin SL 0.3 mg SL Q5MIN:PRN chest pain 
8. Acetaminophen 1000 mg PO Q8H 
9. OxycoDONE (Immediate Release)  ___ mg PO Q4H:PRN pain 
RX *oxycodone 5 mg 1 tablet(s) by mouth q4-6hrs Disp #*30 Tablet 
Refills:*0

 
Discharge Disposition:
Home
 
Discharge Diagnosis:
Bilateral breast invasive ductal carcinoma with bilateral 
axillary lymph node metastases.

 
Discharge Condition:
Mental Status: Clear and coherent.
Level of Consciousness: Alert and interactive.
Activity Status: Ambulatory - Independent.

 
Discharge Instructions:
1. You may keep your incisions open to air or covered with a 
clean, sterile gauze that you change daily. 
2. Clean around the drain site(s), where the tubing exits the 
skin, with soap and water.  
3. Strip drain tubing, empty bulb(s), and record output(s) ___ 
times per day.  
4. A written record of the daily output from each drain should 
be brought to every follow-up appointment. your drains will be 
removed as soon as possible when the daily output tapers off to 
an acceptable amount.  
5. You may wear a surgical bra or soft, loose camisole for 
comfort.  
6. You may shower daily with assistance as needed. Be sure to 
secure your drains so they don't hang down loosely and pull out. 

7. The Dermabond skin glue will begin to flake off in about ___ 
days.  

Activity:  
1. You may resume your regular diet.  
2. Walk several times a day.  
3. DO NOT lift anything heavier than 5 pounds or engage in 
strenuous activity for 6 weeks following surgery. 
Medications:  
1. Resume your regular medications unless instructed otherwise 
and take any new meds as ordered .  
2. You may take your prescribed pain medication for moderate to 
severe pain. You may switch to Tylenol or Extra Strength Tylenol 
for mild pain as directed on the packaging. Please note that 
Percocet and Vicodin have Tylenol as an active ingredient so do 
not take these meds with additional Tylenol.  
3. Take prescription pain medications for pain not relieved by 
Tylenol.  
4. Take Colace, 100 mg by mouth 2 times per day, while taking 
the prescription pain medication. You may use a different 
over-the-counter stool softener if you wish.  
5. Do not drive or operate heavy machinery while taking any 
narcotic pain medication. You may have constipation when taking 
narcotic pain medications (oxycodone, percocet, vicodin, 
hydrocodone, dilaudid, etc.); you should continue drinking 
fluids, you may take stool softeners, and should eat foods that 
are high in fiber.  

Call the office IMMEDIATELY if you have any of the following:  
1. Signs of infection: fever with chills, increased redness, 
swelling, warmth or tenderness at the surgical site, or unusual 
drainage from the incision(s).  
2. A large amount of bleeding from the incision(s) or drain(s).  

3. Fever greater than 101.5 oF  
4. Severe pain NOT relieved by your medication.  
  
Return to the ER if:  
* If you are vomiting and cannot keep in fluids or your 
medications.  
* If you have shaking chills, fever greater than 101.5 (F) 
degrees or 38 (C) degrees, increased redness, swelling or 
discharge from incision, chest pain, shortness of breath, or 
anything else that is troubling you.  
* Any serious change in your symptoms, or any new symptoms that 
concern you.  
DRAIN DISCHARGE INSTRUCTIONS  
You are being discharged with drains in place. Drain care is a 
clean procedure. Wash your hands thoroughly with soap and warm 
water before performing drain care. Perform drainage care twice 
a day. Try to empty the drain at the same time each day. Pull 
the stopper out of the drainage bottle and empty the drainage 
fluid into the measuring cup. Record the amount of drainage 
fluid on the record sheet. Reestablish drain suction.  
Please assist patient with drain care. A daily log of individual 
drain outputs should be maintained and brought with patient to 
follow up appointment with your surgeon.
 
 
 

 
Followup Instructions:
___
"}]

Discharge Instructions:
Personal Care:  
 1. You may leave your incisions open to air or you may cover 
them with a clean, dry dressing daily.  
 2. Clean around the drain site(s), where the tubing exits the 
skin, with soap and water.  
 3. Strip drain tubing, empty bulb(s), and record output(s) ___ 
times per day.  
 4. A written record of the daily output from each drain should 
be brought to every follow-up appointment. Your drains will be 
removed as soon as possible when the daily output tapers off to 
an acceptable amount.  
 5. You may shower daily. No baths until instructed to do so by 
Dr. ___.  
 .  
 Activity:  
 1. You may resume your regular diet.  
 2. DO NOT lift anything heavier than 5 pounds or engage in 
strenuous activity until instructed by Dr. ___.  
 .  
 Medications:  
 1. Resume your regular medications unless instructed otherwise 
and take any new meds as ordered.  
 2. You may take your prescribed pain medication for moderate to 
severe pain. You may switch to Tylenol or Extra Strength Tylenol 
for mild pain as directed on the packaging.    
3. Take Colace, 100 mg by mouth 2 times per day, while taking 
the prescription pain medication. You may use a different 
over-the-counter stool softener if you wish.  
 4.  Do not drive or operate heavy machinery while taking any 
narcotic pain medication. You may have constipation when taking 
narcotic pain medications (oxycodone, percocet, vicodin, 
hydrocodone, dilaudid, etc.); you should continue drinking 
fluids, you may take stool softeners, and should eat foods that 
are high in fiber.  
.

 1. Signs of infection: fever with chills, increased redness, 
swelling, warmth or tenderness at the surgical site, or unusual 
drainage from the incision(s).  
 2. A large amount of bleeding from the incision(s) or drain(s). 
 
 3. Fever greater than 101.5 oF  
 4. Severe pain NOT relieved by your medication.  
 .

 * If you are vomiting and cannot keep in fluids or your 
medications.  
 * If you have shaking chills, fever greater than 101.5 (F) 
degrees or 38 (C) degrees, increased redness, swelling or 
discharge from incision, chest pain, shortness of breath, or 
anything else that is troubling you.  
 * Any serious change in your symptoms, or any new symptoms that 
concern you.  
 .  
DRAIN DISCHARGE INSTRUCTIONS  

You are being discharged with drains in place. Drain care is a 
clean procedure. Wash your hands thoroughly with soap and warm 
water before performing drain care. Perform drainage care twice 
a day. Try to empty the drain at the same time each day. Pull 
the stopper out of the drainage bottle and empty the drainage 
fluid into the measuring cup. Record the amount of drainage 
fluid on the record sheet. Reestablish drain suction.

Nausea

None
 
History of Present Illness:
___ with metastatic breast Ca to liver and spine on aromasin 
started ___, with increasing weakness over the past 3 days, 
stating generalized weakness and lethargy with exertion. Dyspnea 
on exertion when ambulation. Also w/ nausea vomiting for 2 days 
she believe due to her new medication aromasin. Nausea is 
constant but worsened by solids, has been tolerating minimal 
fluids, some mild epigastric discomfort but no clear pain. She 
otherwise denies f/c, head/cp/dysuria, hematemesis, brbpr, 
melena. Weight loss unclear amt over the past month.  
.  
Of note, recent admission from ___ also for nausea, 
thought associated with medications, possibly xeloda at that 
point.  
.  
In ED VS 100.0 initially HR 124 but decreased to 115 with IVF, 
otherwise 115, RR 20 RA, a cxr was otherwise unremarkable. Given 
zofran and 1L IVF,  
 
.

liver/spine mets failed tamoxifan, letrozole recently on xeloda 
complicated by thrombocytopenia, started on aromasin ___  

 
Past Medical History:
1. Right breast CA in ___ s/p chemo+radiation.  
2. Metastatic disease to the liver per CT, ___.  
3. Metastatic disease to the lumbar spine.  
4. Status post kyphoplasty ___  
5. Status post vertebroplasty of ___  

 
Social History:
___
Family History:
 mother died of colon cancer in her ___, no other cancer in the 
family
 
Physical Exam:
VS 99.8 121 20 117/70 94RA  
GEN: NAD, thin appearing, speaking in full sentences

EXT: no c/c/e  
NEURO: CNII-CNXII intact, no focal deficits

___ 09:56PM   GLUCOSE-101 LACTATE-1.5 NA+-136 K+-4.0

___ 10:00PM   WBC-6.3 RBC-2.75* HGB-8.2* HCT-23.7* MCV-86

___ 10:00PM   PLT SMR-VERY LOW PLT COUNT-24*
___ 10:00PM   ___ PTT-25.3 ___
.
CXR: PA and lateral chest radiographs are reviewed and compared 
to ___. Prior CT torso from ___. Cardiomediastinal 
contours are normal and unchanged. Pulmonary vascularity is 
normal. There is increased reticular markings throughout both 
lungs which may be related to technique as lungs were clear on a 
recent CT. There is no pleural effusion or pneumothorax. Post- 
vertebroplasty changes are seen in T7 vertebral body, unchanged 
from CT of ___, allowing for differences in modality.

 
Brief Hospital Course:
___ woman with metastatic breast cancer presented with 
nausea and vomiting.  
.  
# Breast cancer: she received trastuzumab in house. The infusion 
was initially stopped half-way as the patient developed rigors, 
fever, and hypotension. Premedication with IV steroids the 
following day lead to an uneventful infusion of the second half 
of the trastuzumab dose.
.  
# Nausea/vomiting: resolved with antiemetics. Patient was able 
to tolerate PO well by discharge. 
.  
# Hypercalcemia: likely from malignancy with bone mets. Got IVF, 
pamidronate 90 mg IV x 1 ___ and was given calcitonin. Her Ca 
trended down to normal by discharge, and the calcitonin was 
discontinued.
.  
# Anemia/thrombycytopenia: evidence of hemolysis on labs and 
smear. Likely malignancy-related with Abs against RBC membrane 
components. She was transfused with pRBCs and platelets. 
.  
# Code: DNR/DNI  
 
Medications on Admission:
Exemestane [Aromasin] 25mg Daily  
MEGESTROL 400 mg/10 mL Suspension - 10 cc BID  
Omeprazole 40 mg Daily 

 
Discharge Medications:
1. Omeprazole 40 mg Capsule, Delayed Release(E.C.) Sig: One (1) 
Capsule, Delayed Release(E.C.) PO once a day.  
2. Prochlorperazine Maleate 10 mg Tablet Sig: One (1) Tablet PO 
Q6H (every 6 hours) as needed for nausea.  
3. Megace Oral 400 mg/10 mL Suspension Sig: Ten (10) ml PO twice 
a day.  
4. Aromasin 25 mg Tablet Sig: One (1) Tablet PO once a day.  

 
Discharge Disposition:
Home With Service
 
Facility:
___
 
Discharge Diagnosis:
Primary diagnoses: metastatic breast cancer, hypercalcemia

Secondary diagnoses: breast cancer
 
Discharge Condition:
Stable
 
Discharge Instructions:
You presented to ___ with nausea and vomiting. You were found 
to have high calcium levels and received intravenous fluids and 
medications to lower the calcium to normal level. You were given 
trastuzumab (Herceptin) for your breast cancer. You received 
blood and platelet transfusions. Your nausea and vomiting 
resolved by discharge.

Please take all your medications and go to your follow-up 
appointments as instructed. If you develop recurrent nausea, 
vomiting, weakness, fevers, chills, or any concerning symptom, 
please call your doctor or go to the nearest ER immediately.

___

RX *hydromorphone 2 mg 1 tablet(s) by mouth every four (4) hours

Left Ductal Carcinoma in-situ

Mental Status: Clear and coherent.

Discharge Instructions:
Discharge instructions: 
Personal Care: 
1. You may keep your incisions open to air or covered with a 
clean, sterile gauze that you change daily. If any areas develop 

blistering, you will need to apply Bactroban cream twice a day.  


2. Clean around the drain site(s), where the tubing exits the 
skin, with soap and water.  
3. Strip drain tubing, empty bulb(s), and record output(s) ___ 
times per day.  
4. A written record of the daily output from each drain should 
be brought to every follow-up appointment. your drains will be 
removed as soon as possible when the daily output tapers off to 
an acceptable amount.  
5. DO NOT wear a normal bra for 3 weeks. You may wear a soft, 
loose camisole for comfort.   
6. You may shower daily with assistance as needed. Be sure to 
secure your upper drains to a lanyard that hangs down from your 
neck so they don't hang down and pull out. You may secure your 
lower drains to a fabric belt tied around your waist. 
7. The Dermabond skin glue will begin to flake off in about ___ 

days. 
 8. No pressure on your chest or abdomen  
9. Okay to shower, but no baths until after directed by your 
doctor.   

Activity: 
 1. You may resume your regular diet.   
2. Keep hips flexed at all times, and then gradually stand 
upright as tolerated. 
 3. DO NOT lift anything heavier than 5 pounds or engage in 
strenuous activity for 6 weeks following surgery.  

  Medications:  
1. Resume your regular medications unless instructed otherwise 
and take any new meds as ordered .  
2. You may take your prescribed pain medication for moderate to 
severe pain. You may switch to Tylenol or Extra Strength Tylenol 

for mild pain as directed on the packaging. 
3. Take prescription pain medications for pain not relieved by 
tylenol. 
4. Take Colace, 100 mg by mouth 2 times per day, while taking 
the prescription pain medication. You may use a different 
over-the-counter stool softener if you wish.  
5. Do not drive or operate heavy machinery while taking any 
narcotic pain medication. You may have constipation when taking 
narcotic pain medications (oxycodone, percocet, vicodin, 
hydrocodone, dilaudid, etc.); you should continue drinking 
fluids, you may take stool softeners, and should eat foods that 
are high in fiber.  .

  Call the office IMMEDIATELY if you have any of the following:  

1. Signs of infection: fever with chills, increased redness, 
swelling, warmth or tenderness at the surgical site, or unusual 
drainage from the incision(s).  
2. A large amount of bleeding from the incision(s) or drain(s).  


3. Fever greater than 101.5 oF  
4. Severe pain NOT relieved by your medication.  . 

 Return to the ER if:   
* If you are vomiting and cannot keep in fluids or your 
medications.   
* If you have shaking chills, fever greater than 101.5 (F) 
degrees or 38 (C) degrees, increased redness, swelling or 
discharge from incision, chest pain, shortness of breath, or 
anything else that is troubling you.  
* Any serious change in your symptoms, or any new symptoms that 
concern you.  .  

DRAIN DISCHARGE INSTRUCTIONS  You are being discharged with 
drains in place. Drain care is a clean procedure. Wash your 
hands thoroughly with soap and warm water before performing 
drain care. Perform drainage care twice a day. Try to empty the 
drain at the same time each day. Pull the stopper out of the 
drainage bottle and empty the drainage fluid into the measuring 
cup. Record the amount of drainage fluid on the record sheet. 
Reestablish drain suction.

 
Followup Instructions:
___
